One simple idea that shifted my approach to communication:

Say more "thank you's" and fewer "sorry's"

Thank you for your patience vs. Sorry I'm late
Thank you for your time vs. Sorry this took so long
Thank you for understanding vs. Sorry that got messed up

🧵...
Thank you communicates appreciation for others. It recognizes the sacrifice/contribution of others. It is productive, net positive, and deepens relationships. And it does not accept guilt/shame.
"Sorry" communicates acceptance of blame and with it often shame/guilt. It makes the conversation about your feeling bad versus the feelings of those who may have been slighted.
Don't get me wrong. You mess up big, you apologize. But we spend way too much energy on "sorry" when a sincere "thank you" is actually what is needed to set things right and move forward.
